title: For Sale:  1866 Chassepot Rifle Chatellernault Armenment Carbine
postcontent:
I have a 1866 Chassepot Rifle Carbine by Chatellernault Armenment. This is the first gun of this age I have had and I don't know a lot about the gun except what I've read on the internet and I'm not sure if I will get all the language correct for listing. I'm going to list everything the gun reads for a description. I don't know if this gun was modified from the ones captured by Russia in the war and modified by them. I know there was close to a 1,000,000 of these guns captured, redesigned and reissued to the Russian army as carbines.
The gun measures 37 5/8" long, the stock has a small crack below bolt. The barrel itself does have some dings along the right side, that look to me like it has been stored with other guns. The blueing has turned to the metal tint as a older shotgun does. Its missing the original ram rod and the military sight, the inside of the barrel is very clean, no real signs of pitting.
Here's how the gun reads starting with the barrel:
The left side- F 19731 P.G. with letters B & D in a circle
Right side- S 1870 & S 1876
Reciever Left side- 1866 Chatellernault Armenment M 1866 underneath that
 (?) 1870-1871 France cal. st Alb VI
I believe gun bolt has been replaced with a striker and gas vent, there's no needle, but looks to have a firing pin like a shotgun. 
Would be willing do some trading on the rifle for newer rifle or shotgun.

FFL.OOAK THIS IS A CURRENT LISTING UPDATED 10/02/2014 0700
Lifetime Warranty from Taurus

The PT22 is a .22LR semi-automatic pistol produced by Taurus and features an 8+1 round capacity magazine. The PT22 is often viewed as a Taurus copy of the Beretta 21 Bobcat due to having a similar "tip up" barrel. In fact this small pistol is Very Different in design and function from the Beretta. The PT22 is a cast steel frame and slide, manufactured in Florida, USA. It has a spur-less hammer, and a long but smooth double action only (DAO) trigger. 
The grip feel of the PT22 is "fat", and fills a normal-sized hand perfectly.
Something these little Taurus pistols have been praised for is the tip-up barrel design. What looks something like a slide release on the left side of the gun is actually a barrel release. Press it forward and the rear of the barrel pops up for loading a round directly into the chamber. To load the PT-22, then, simply load the magazine with cartridges, fully insert the magazine into the butt of the gun until it catches, pop up the barrel, insert a cartridge, and snap the barrel back down into the closed position.  
There is no need to rack the slide, which is a benefit to those who, because of arthritis or other hand weakness, are unable to operate conventional auto pistols.

title: For Sale:  ***TOP NOTCH SECURITY CENTERS INC CUSTOMER SERVICE EXPERIENCE
postcontent:
I just thought I'd share my recent experience with Security Centers Inc. located in Catoosa.

I called originally from their listing on the scratch and dent sale.  I spoke with Dee, who was EXTREMELY nice and helpful.  Hands down head and shoulders above 99.9% of employees at ANY business in regards to attitude and customer service.  She went to the back to check the inventory left before I drove out to the location by the hard rock in Catoosa.  I ended up driving in that day (a busy Saturday mind you)  and patiently waited while they diligently tended to previous customers.  I was helped by Dee's son (it's a family affair), who was more than helpful in answering my questions and I mentioned the ad to get a free dehumidifier.  I couldn't take it home that day due to the vehicle I was in.  They replied "no problem!  We'd be happy to hold it for you until you can arrange pickup".  

That being said, they close at 5 on weekdays.  I NEVER get off before 530 during the week, but today had a Dr apt for my daughter so I was off at 3pm.  I called and said I was going to try to make it today (10/21).  Ended up that it was 430 and I was just able to head that way from deep south BA.  I called and the owners gladly and willingly stayed until after close to aid in my safe pickup.  The owner even helped load it with me, as the rest of his staff was gone for the day.  This is going above and beyond imo.  

Moral of the story is if you're in the market for a gun safe, you'd be doing yourself a disservice by not at least giving SCI a shot.  I'll tell everybody I know in the gun world about them and their service!  Top notch service, top notch products and prices.

**I have zero affiliation or ties with the company, or any of its employees and they had no idea I was going to post this "review".  I received no discount aside from the scratch and dent prices and the free dehumidifier.

title: For Sale:  Sistema .45acp (Colt Clone from Argentina, made in 1952)
postcontent:
The Colt Sistema was produced by Fabrica Militar de Armas Portatiles (FMAP) in Argentina. Production began at the Esteban de Luca Arsenal in Buenos Aires, with the first pistols actually being assembled at the Domingo Matheu plant in Rosario, Argentina in 1945. It is also known as the Pistola Sistema "Colt" Modelo Argentino 1927, Calibre 11.25mm, which is basically a 1911 of 1927 vintage built on Colt equipment to Colt specifications.

Sistemas were built from 1945 to 1966, and represent one of the best deals available in a genuine GI 1911. Here are the serial numbers by year, along with the production numbers.

Based on serial number, this one was made in 1952.
